gland":"Stisted, Essex, England, United Kingdom","Stisted, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Stisted, Essex, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1312–":"1312–Overleden","1307–1375":"1307–1375","1350–1397":"1350–1397","1312–Female":"1312–Overleden","1312":"1312","1332":"1332","1397":"1397","1375":"1375","1350":"1350","1307":"1307","Stisted, Essex, England":"Stisted, Essex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Stisted, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Stisted, Essex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1312–":"1312–Deceased","1307–1375":"1307–1375","1350–1397":"1350–1397","1312–Female":"1312–Deceased","1312":"1312","1332":"1332","1397":"1397","1375":"1375","1350":"1350","1307":"1307","Stisted, Essex, England":"Stisted, Essex, England, United Kingdom","Stisted, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Stisted, Essex, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Alston","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish:","from the Middle English personal name <i>Alstan</i>, which is a coalescence of several different Old English personal names: <i>Æthelstān</i> ‘noble stone’, <i>Ælfstān</i> ‘elf stone’, <i>Ealdstān</i> ‘old stone’, or <i>Ealhstān</i> ‘temple stone’.","habitational name from any of various places called Alston (in Cumbria, Lancashire, Devon, and Somerset) or Alstone (in Gloucestershire and Staffordshire). With the exception of Alston in Cumbria, which is formed with the Old Norse personal name <i>Halfdan</i>, these placenames all consist of an Old English personal name + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement’, for example <i>Ælfsige</i> in the case of Alstone in Gloucestershire."],"variants":[{"name":"Aston","meanings":["English:","from the Middle English personal name <i>Ad(e)stan</i>, which is usually from Old English <i>Æthelstān</i> (see   Alston  ). It may also be from the much rarer Old English name <i>Ēadstān</i>.","habitational name from any of several places in England called Aston. Most were named with Old English <i>ēast</i> ‘east’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement’. In a few cases the first element is <i>æsc</i> ‘ash tree’."]},{"name":"Allston","meanings":["English: variant of   Alston  ."]},{"name":"Hailstone","meanings":["habitational name from Hailstone Hill in Wiltshire or Hailstone Farm in Gloucestershire, the former of which may be derived from Old English <i>hālig-stān</i> ‘holy stone’ or <i>hagolstān</i> ‘hailstone’ (Middle English <i>hawelston</i>, <i>hailston</i>).","from <i>Ailstan</i>, a variant of the Old English personal name <i>Æthelstān</i> (‘noble’ + ‘stone’), with prosthetic initial <i>H-</i>. The first element of the Old English name developed from <i>Æthel-</i> to <i>Ægel-</i> and then to <i>Ail-</i>; it was often further shortened to <i>Al-</i> (see   Alston  ).","English:"]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. William Stristed Alston was born in 1312, in Stisted, Essex, England, United Kingdom. She married William Alston of Stristed in 1332, in Stisted, Essex, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in her hometown."},"et":{"1312–":"1312–Surnud","1307–1375":"1307–1375","1350–1397":"1350–1397","1312–Female":"1312–Surnud","1312":"1312","1332":"1332",